  "dateModified": "2025-12-30",
  "datePublished": "2025-12-30",
  "description": "Kevin B. Anderson\u0026rsquo;s The Late Marx and the Russian Road has become the canonical reference for a plural, non-Eurocentric Marx. Its archival recovery of Marx\u0026rsquo;s ethnological notebooks is invaluable, yet the book\u0026rsquo;s form and reception reveal a deeper process: the translation of a scientific attempt to understand social formations into a moral narrative that organizes belief. This article reconstructs that process as it occurs in Anderson\u0026rsquo;s text. Drawing on Bourdieu\u0026rsquo;s sociology of intellectual fields, Kuhn and Lakatos\u0026rsquo;s philosophy of scientific change, and the decolonial analyses of Fanon, Wynter, Berlant, Coulthard, Simpson, and de Sousa Santos, the essay shows how Anderson\u0026rsquo;s reading turns Marx\u0026rsquo;s late uncertainty into evidence of virtue, transforming an unfinished research program into a story of redemption. It concludes by outlining the methodological work required to recover Anderson\u0026rsquo;s materials for an empirically testable, collaborative, and decolonial social science.\n",
  "name": "From science to story, reading The Late Marx as morality",
